## 3. Dual-Mode Architecture — Purchase & Sales

### The Core Concept

The entire ERP runs two completely separate ledgers — Purchase and Sales — from one codebase. This is the most important architectural concept in the whole app.

```javascript
let DB = {
  mode: 'purchase',       // Active module. Always starts on Purchase.
  purchase: _blankModule(),
  sales:    _blankModule(),
};

function AD() { return DB.mode === 'sales' ? DB.sales : DB.purchase; }
```

`AD()` — **Active Dataset** — is the single pointer through which ALL page renders, form saves, and CRUD functions operate. No function directly touches `DB.purchase` or `DB.sales`. They all call `AD()`. This means every feature (invoice form, payment list, statement, etc.) is automatically mode-aware with zero extra code per feature.

### What Each Module Contains (`_blankModule()`)
```javascript
function _blankModule() {
  return {
    records:        [],   // Invoice / bill records
    payments:       [],   // Payment records
    cheques:        [],   // NOT used here — shared via CHQ()
    deliveryNotes:  [],   // Delivery note records
    nextId:         1,    // Auto-increment record counter
    nextInv:        1,    // Auto-increment invoice number
    nextDN:         1,    // Auto-increment delivery note number
    customParties:  [],   // User-added parties/vendors/customers
    customDescs:    [],   // User-added item descriptions
    customUnits:    [],   // User-added units of measure
    customMethods:  [],   // User-added payment methods
    customPaidBy:   []    // User-added "paid by" names
  };
}
```

### The Shared Cheque Register

Cheques are intentionally **not** scoped to either module. They live in one shared Firebase node (`almadhi/cheques`) and one in-memory array:

```javascript
function CHQ()      { return DB.purchase.cheques; }   // Single source of truth
function CHQ_ROOT() { return 'almadhi'; }
```

Reason: A cheque may be issued by a supplier (purchase context) but cleared on the bank account (not mode-specific). Keeping them shared prevents a supplier's cheque from disappearing when someone switches to Sales mode.

### Firebase Path Routing

```javascript
function MODE_ROOT(mode) {
  return (mode || DB.mode) === 'sales' ? 'almadhi/sales' : 'almadhi';
}
```

- Purchase data lives at: `almadhi/records`, `almadhi/payments`, `almadhi/deliveryNotes`, `almadhi/meta`, `almadhi/custom`
- Sales data lives at: `almadhi/sales/records`, `almadhi/sales/payments`, etc.
- Cheques live at: `almadhi/cheques` (shared)
- Settings live at: `almadhi/settings` (shared)

This means no data migration was ever needed — Sales was added as a new parallel namespace.

### Mode Switching

```javascript
function setAppMode(mode) {
  DB.mode = mode;
  document.body.classList.toggle('mode-sales', mode === 'sales');
  // Refreshes all dropdowns, re-renders current page, updates menu highlights
}
```

Switching mode is **instant** because both modules' Firebase listeners are active simultaneously (attached at startup for both `purchase` and `sales` roots). When data arrives for either module, it loads into `DB.purchase` or `DB.sales` immediately. The sidebar toggle is never waiting for a fresh fetch.

### Mode-Specific Built-in Data

```javascript
const BUILTIN_DESCS_BY_MODE = {
  purchase: [
    { name:'PURCHASE WOOD',              unit:'TON' },
    { name:'PURCHASE WOOD (SMALL WOOD)', unit:'TON' },
    { name:'PALLET PURCHASE',            unit:'PCS' },
    { name:'GUTKA PURCHASE',             unit:'KG'  },
  ],
