## 23. Offline Read-Cache System

### Architecture

Firebase is the ONLY source of truth — there is no localStorage primary store. However, to enable reading data when offline, a snapshot of the current data is saved to localStorage after every successful Firebase update:

```javascript
function cacheDB() {
  try {
    localStorage.setItem('almadhi_cache_' + DB.mode, JSON.stringify({
      records:  AD().records,
      payments: AD().payments,
      cheques:  CHQ(),
      nextId:   AD().nextId,
      nextInv:  AD().nextInv,
      custom:   { parties, descs, units, methods, paidby },
      ts:       Date.now()
    }));
  } catch(e) {}
}
```

### Hydration on Startup

When the app starts, before Firebase data arrives, `hydrateFromCache()` loads the localStorage snapshot:

```javascript
function hydrateFromCache() {
  if(AD().records.length) return;  // Firebase already populated — skip
  // Load cache into DB arrays
  // Use Math.max for sequence numbers (prevent regression)
}
```

This gives instant read-access to old data while Firebase connects. The user sees their last-session records immediately, then the live Firebase data replaces it when the connection is ready.

### Read-Only vs. Read-Write Offline

Offline reads are always available (from cache). Offline writes go to `window._writeQueue` and show a "Offline — write queued" toast. There is no optimistic local commit pattern — the data is only rendered after Firebase confirms. This is deliberate: it prevents showing data that hasn't been verified as persisted.

